‘Wealth has no value save to use well: used as Proculeius used it, it wins immortal farne. To tame the spirit of avarice is more than to own the world. Avarice is like the thirst of dropsy, which grows by indulgence. Virtue calls him alone happy, him alone the true king, who has subdued the love of money.‘

That the Ode is addressed to Salustius is enough to show that there could be no danger of the world's applying its doctrine to him.

The little we know of him is chiefly derived from Tacitus, Ann. 3. 30, where his death in AJ). 20 is recorded: ⁴ Crispum, equestri loco, C.
